---
import { Content as BeforeCode } from './code.mdx';

import './CodeSection.css';
---

<section class="code-section">
  <h2>See It In Action</h2>
  <p class="section-subtitle">
    CSS is nice and powerful, but lacking things we're used to in coding, like <b>re-usable</b> selectors,
    <b>compile-time</b> and <b>type safety</b>, a direct <b>JS interface</b>, <b>composability</b> etc.
    <br />
    Typescript already solves all of this - and Surimi takes advantage of that.
  </p>

  <div class="code-comparison">
    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-header">
        <span class="code-label">Some examples of Surimi code</span>
        <a href="/playground">
          <button class="code-button"> See more in the playground </button>
        </a>
      </div>
      <BeforeCode />
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="pro-tip">
    <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> With Surimi, you get full TypeScript type checking, autocomplete for property names and values,
    and instant feedback on typos or invalid CSS. If you change a selector (like <code>.container</code>), all related
    styles update automatically.
  </div>
</section>
